# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: confidential-computing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] The technology protects data in use by performing computations in a hardware-based trusted execution environment (TEE).
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential data is released to the TEE only once it is assessed to be trustworthy.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Different types of confidential computing define the level of data isolation used, whether virtual machine, application, or function, and the technology can be deployed in on-premise data centers, edge locations, or the public cloud.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] It is often compared with other privacy-enhancing computational techniques such as fully homomorphic encryption, secure multi-party computation, and Trusted Computing.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing is promoted by the Confidential Computing Consortium (CCC) industry group, whose membership includes major providers of the technology.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Trusted execution environments (TEEs) "prevent unauthorized access or modification of applications and data while they are in use, thereby increasing the security level of organizations that manage sensitive and regulated data".
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Trusted execution environments can be instantiated on a computer's processing components such as a central processing unit (CPU) or a graphics processing unit (GPU).
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] In their various implementations, TEEs can provide different levels of isolation including virtual machine, individual application, or compute functions.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Typically, data in use in a computer's compute components and memory exists in a decrypted state and can be vulnerable to examination or tampering by unauthorized software or administrators.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] In addition to trusted execution environments, remote cryptographic attestation is an essential part of confidential computing.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] The attestation process assesses the trustworthiness of a system and helps ensure that confidential data is released to a TEE only after it presents verifiable evidence that it is genuine and operating with an acceptable security posture.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] It allows the verifying party to assess the trustworthiness of a confidential computing environment through an "authentic, accurate, and timely report about the software and data state" of that environment.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] "Hardware-based attestation schemes rely on a trusted hardware component and associated firmware to execute attestation routines in a secure environment".
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Without attestation, a compromised system could deceive others into trusting it, claim it is running certain software in a TEE, and potentially compromise the confidentiality or integrity of the data being processed or the integrity of the trusted code.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Technical approaches to confidential computing may vary in which software, infrastructure and administrator elements are allowed to access confidential data.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] The "trust boundary," which circumscribes a trusted computing base (TCB), defines which elements have the potential to access confidential data, whether they are acting benignly or maliciously.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing implementations enforce the defined trust boundary at a specific level of data isolation.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Virtual machine isolation removes the elements controlled by the computer infrastructure or cloud provider, but allows potential data access by elements inside a virtual machine running on the infrastructure.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Application or process isolation permits data access only by authorized software applications or processes.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Function or library isolation is designed to permit data access only by authorized subroutines or modules within a larger application, blocking access by any other system element, including unauthorized code in the larger application.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] As confidential computing is concerned with the protection of data in use, only certain threat models can be addressed by this technique.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Other types of attacks are better addressed by other privacy-enhancing technologies.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] The degree and mechanism of protection against these threats varies with specific confidential computing implementations.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing can be deployed in the public cloud, on-premise data centers, or distributed "edge" locations, including network nodes, branch offices, industrial systems and others.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing protects the confidentiality and integrity of data and code from the infrastructure provider, unauthorized or malicious software and system administrators, and other cloud tenants, which may be a concern for organizations seeking control over sensitive or regulated data.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] The additional security capabilities offered by confidential computing can help accelerate the transition of more sensitive workloads to the cloud or edge locations.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing can enable multiple parties to engage in joint analysis using confidential or regulated data inside a TEE while preserving privacy and regulatory compliance.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] In this case, all parties benefit from the shared analysis, but no party's sensitive data or confidential code is exposed to the other parties or system host.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Examples include multiple healthcare organizations contributing data to medical research, or multiple banks collaborating to identify financial fraud or money laundering.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing technologies can be applied to various stages of a generative AI deployments to help increase data or model privacy, security, and regulatory compliance.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] TEEs and remote attestation can protect the integrity of data during AI model training, keep non-public data confidential during inference or Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG), and protect the AI model itself from various adversarial attacks or theft.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing assists in data protection and regulatory compliance by limiting which software and people may access regulated data, as well as providing greater assurance of data and code integrity.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] In addition, TEEs can assist with data governance by providing evidence of steps taken to mitigate risks and demonstrate that these were appropriate.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] In 2021, the European Union Agency for Cybersecurity (ENISA) classifies confidential computing as a "State of the Art" technology with respect to protecting data under the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation and Germany's IT Security Act (ITSiG).
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Regulations regarding data localization and residency or data sovereignty may require that sensitive data remain in a specific country or geographic bloc to provide assurance that the data will only be used in compliance with local law.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Using confidential computing, only the workload owner holds the encryption keys required to decrypt data for processing inside a verified TEE.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] This provides a technological safeguard that reduces the risk of data being exfiltrated and processed in plaintext in other countries or jurisdictions without the workload owner's consent.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Additional use cases for confidential computing include blockchain applications with enhanced record privacy and code integrity, privacy-preserving advertising technology, confidential databases and more.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Multiple academic and security research groups have demonstrated architectural and side-channel attacks against CPU-based TEEs based on a variety of approaches.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] These include page faults, caching, and the memory bus, as well as specifically Æpic and SGAxe against Intel SGX, and CIPHERLEAKS against AMD SEV-SNP.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Update mechanisms in the hardware, such as Trusted computing base (TCB) recovery, can mitigate side-channel vulnerabilities as they are discovered.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] The definition of confidential computing itself has also been criticized by some academic researchers.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Scholars at the Technical University of Dresden, Germany called it, "imprecise, incomplete and even conflicting." Researchers have made recommendations to make it more detailed and exact to facilitate research and comparisons with other security technologies.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] "Confidential Remote Computing" (CRC) paradigm, claims to revert confidential computing to original design principles of TEEs and advocate for small enclaves, running in available end-users computers.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] CRC adds practices and templates for multiple stakeholders, such as different data owners, hardware owners and algorithm owners.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] CRC extends the broad notion of confidential computing by adding practices and methodologies for individual use.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] None of the major microprocessor or GPU providers offer Confidential computing hardware in devices for personal computers anymore, which limits use cases only to server-class platforms.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Intel SGX was introduced for PCs in 6th Generation Intel Core (Skylake) processors in 2015, but deprecated in the 11th Generation Intel Core processors (Rocket Lake) in 2022.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing is often compared to other security or privacy-enhancing technologies, including fully homomorphic encryption, secure multi-party computing and trusted computing.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Fully homomorphic encryption (FHE) is a form of encryption that permits users to perform computations on encrypted data without first decrypting it.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing, in contrast, transfers encrypted data inside a hardware-enforced, access-controlled TEE in the processor and memory, decrypts the data, and performs the required computations.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Data may be re-encrypted before exiting the TEE.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Compared to each other, FHE performance can suffer from higher computational overhead than confidential computing and require extensive application-specific coding but is less susceptible to side-channel attacks since data is never decrypted.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Several researchers have described use cases where confidential computing TEEs and FHE work together to mitigate shortcomings of the technologies acting individually.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Secure multi-party computation (SMPC) is a privacy-preserving technology that allows multiple parties to jointly compute a task using distributed algorithms while keeping each party's data private from the others.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing can also be used for privacy-preserving multi-party collaboration.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Compared to each other, distributed computing with SMPC can be more expensive in terms of computation and network bandwidth, but less susceptible to side-channel attacks since no party ever holds the complete data set.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Trusted computing is a concept and set of standards published by the Trusted Computing Group that aim to establish trust in computing systems by using standardized hardware-based mechanisms like the Trusted Platform Module (TPM).
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] From a technical perspective, Trusted Computing and confidential computing rely on similar security concepts, such as trust architecture and remote attestation protocols.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing use cases require a combination of hardware and software, often delivered in conjunction with cloud service providers or server manufacturers.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing technology and services can be accessed via public cloud computing providers, including Alibaba Cloud, Baidu Cloud, Google Cloud, IBM Cloud, Microsoft Azure, OVHcloud and others.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Application software is required to enable most confidential computing use cases.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Providers of confidential computing software applications include Anjuna, CanaryBit, Cosmian, CYSEC, Decentriq, Duality, Edgeless Systems, Enclaive, Fortanix, IBM Hyper Protect Services, Mithril Security, Oblivious, Opaque Systems, Scontain, Secretarium, Super Protocol, Fr0ntierX, and others.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] Confidential computing is supported by an advocacy and technical collaboration group called the Confidential Computing Consortium.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] The CCC was formed in 2019 under the Linux Foundation.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] The founding premiere members were Alibaba, Arm, Google Cloud, Huawei, Intel, Microsoft and Red Hat.
[src:confidential-computing/confidential-computing] The founding general members included SUSE, Baidu, ByteDance, Decentriq, Fortanix, Kindite, Oasis Labs, Swisscom, Tencent and VMware.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Digital data can be contrasted with *analog data*, which is represented by a value from a continuous range of real numbers.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Analog data is transmitted by an analog signal, which not only takes on continuous values but can vary continuously with time, a continuous real-valued function of time.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] An example is the air pressure variation in a sound wave.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data requires interpretation to become information.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In modern (post-1960) computer systems, all data is digital.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The word *digital* comes from the same source as the words digit and *digitus* (the Latin word for *finger*), as fingers are often used for counting.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Mathematician George Stibitz of Bell Telephone Laboratories used the word *digital* in reference to the fast electric pulses emitted by a device designed to aim and fire anti-aircraft guns in 1942.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The term is most commonly used in computing and electronics, especially where real-world information is converted to binary numeric form as in digital audio and digital photography.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Since symbols (for example, alphanumeric characters) are not continuous, representing symbols digitally is rather simpler than conversion of continuous or analog information to digital.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Instead of sampling and quantization as in analog-to-digital conversion, such techniques as polling and encoding are used.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] A symbol input device usually consists of a group of switches that are polled at regular intervals to see which switches are switched.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data will be lost if, within a single polling interval, two switches are pressed, or a switch is pressed, released, and pressed again.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] This polling can be done by a specialized processor in the device to prevent burdening the main CPU.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] When a new symbol has been entered, the device typically sends an interrupt, in a specialized format, so that the CPU can read it.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] For devices with only a few switches (such as the buttons on a joystick), the status of each can be encoded as bits (usually 0 for released and 1 for pressed) in a single word.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] This is useful when combinations of key presses are meaningful, and is sometimes used for passing the status of modifier keys on a keyboard (such as shift and control).
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] But it does not scale to support more keys than the number of bits in a single byte or word.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Devices with many switches (such as a computer keyboard) usually arrange these switches in a scan matrix, with the individual switches on the intersections of x and y lines.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] When a switch is pressed, it connects the corresponding x and y lines together.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Polling (often called scanning in this case) is done by activating each x line in sequence and detecting which y lines then have a signal, thus which keys are pressed.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] When the keyboard processor detects that a key has changed state, it sends a signal to the CPU indicating the scan code of the key and its new state.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The symbol is then encoded or converted into a number based on the status of modifier keys and the desired character encoding.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] A custom encoding can be used for a specific application with no loss of data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] However, using a standard encoding such as ASCII is problematic if a symbol such as 'ß' needs to be converted but is not in the standard.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] It is estimated that in the year 1986, less than 1% of the world's technological capacity to store information was digital and in 2007 it was already 94%.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The year 2002 is assumed to be the year when humankind was able to store more information in digital than in analog format (the "beginning of the digital age").
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Digital data come in these three states: data at rest, data in transit, and data in use.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The confidentiality, integrity, and availability have to be managed during the entire lifecycle from 'birth' to the destruction of the data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] While it is generally accepted that archive data (i.e. which never changes), regardless of its storage medium, is data at rest and active data subject to constant or frequent change is data in use. “Inactive data” could be taken to mean data which may change, but infrequently.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The imprecise nature of terms such as “constant” and “frequent” means that some stored data cannot be comprehensively defined as either data at rest or in use.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] These definitions could be taken to assume that Data at Rest is a superset of data in use; however, data in use, subject to frequent change, has distinct processing requirements from data at rest, whether completely static or subject to occasional change.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Because of its nature data at rest is of increasing concern to businesses, government agencies and other institutions.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data encryption, which prevents data visibility in the event of its unauthorized access or theft, is commonly used to protect data in motion and increasingly promoted for protecting data at rest.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The encryption of data at rest should only include strong encryption methods such as AES or RSA.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Encrypted data should remain encrypted when access controls such as usernames and password fail.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Increasing encryption on multiple levels is recommended.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Cryptography can be implemented on the database housing the data and on the physical storage where the databases are stored.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data encryption keys should be updated on a regular basis.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Encryption keys should be stored separately from the data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Encryption also enables crypto-shredding at the end of the data or hardware lifecycle.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Periodic auditing of sensitive data should be part of policy and should occur on scheduled occurrences.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Finally, only store the minimum possible amount of sensitive data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Tokenization is a non-mathematical approach to protecting data at rest that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes, referred to as tokens, which have no extrinsic or exploitable meaning or value.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] This process does not alter the type or length of data, which means it can be processed by legacy systems such as databases that may be sensitive to data length and type.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Tokens require significantly less computational resources to process and less storage space in databases than traditionally encrypted data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] This is achieved by keeping specific data fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Lower processing and storage requirements makes tokenization an ideal method of securing data at rest in systems that manage large volumes of data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] A further method of preventing unwanted access to data at rest is the use of data federation especially when data is distributed globally (e.g. in off-shore archives).
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] An example of this would be a European organisation which stores its archived data off-site in the US.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Under the terms of the USA PATRIOT Act the American authorities can demand access to all data physically stored within its boundaries, even if it includes personal information on European citizens with no connections to the US.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data encryption alone cannot be used to prevent this as the authorities have the right to demand decrypted information.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] A data federation policy which retains personal citizen information with no foreign connections within its country of origin (separate from information which is either not personal or is relevant to off-shore authorities) is one option to address this concern.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] However, data stored in foreign countries can be accessed using legislation in the CLOUD Act.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Some cloud software as a service (SaaS) providers refer to data in use as any data currently being processed by applications, as the CPU and memory are utilized.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Because of its nature, data in use is of increasing concern to businesses, government agencies and other institutions.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data in use, or memory, can contain sensitive data including digital certificates, encryption keys, intellectual property (software algorithms, design data), and personally identifiable information.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Compromising data in use enables access to encrypted data at rest and data in motion.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] For example, someone with access to random access memory can parse that memory to locate the encryption key for data at rest.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Once they have obtained that encryption key, they can decrypt encrypted data at rest.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Threats to data in use can come in the form of cold boot attacks, malicious hardware devices, rootkits and bootkits.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Encryption, which prevents data visibility in the event of its unauthorized access or theft, is commonly used to protect Data in Motion and Data at Rest and increasingly recognized as an optimal method for protecting Data in Use.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] There have been multiple projects to encrypt memory.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Microsoft Xbox systems are designed to provide memory encryption and the company PrivateCore presently has a commercial software product vCage to provide attestation along with full memory encryption for x86 servers.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Several papers have been published highlighting the availability of security-enhanced x86 and ARM commodity processors.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In that work, an ARM Cortex-A8 processor is used as the substrate on which a full memory encryption solution is built.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Process segments (for example, stack, code or heap) can be encrypted individually or in composition.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] This work marks the first full memory encryption implementation on a mobile general-purpose commodity processor.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The system provides both confidentiality and integrity protections of code and data which are encrypted everywhere outside the CPU boundary.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] For x86 systems, AMD has a Secure Memory Encryption (SME) feature introduced in 2017 with Epyc.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Intel has promised to deliver its Total Memory Encryption (TME) feature in an upcoming CPU.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Operating system kernel patches such as TRESOR and Loop-Amnesia modify the operating system so that CPU registers can be used to store encryption keys and avoid holding encryption keys in RAM.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] While this approach is not general purpose and does not protect all data in use, it does protect against cold boot attacks.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Encryption keys are held inside the CPU rather than in RAM so that data at rest encryption keys are protected against attacks that might compromise encryption keys in memory.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Enclaves enable an “enclave” to be secured with encryption in RAM so that enclave data is encrypted while in RAM but available as clear text inside the CPU and CPU cache.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Intel Corporation has introduced the concept of “enclaves” as part of its Software Guard Extensions.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Intel revealed an architecture combining software and CPU hardware in technical papers published in 2013.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Several cryptographic tools, including secure multi-party computation and homomorphic encryption, allow for the private computation of data on untrusted systems.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data in use could be operated upon while encrypted and never exposed to the system doing the processing.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data in transit can be separated into two categories: information that flows over the public or untrusted network such as the Internet and data that flows in the confines of a private network such as a corporate or enterprise local area network (LAN).
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data within a computer, in most cases, moves as parallel data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data moving to or from a computer, in most cases, moves as serial data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data sourced from an analog device, such as a temperature sensor, may be converted to digital using an analog-to-digital converter.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data representing quantities, characters, or symbols on which operations are performed by a computer are stored and recorded on magnetic, optical, electronic, or mechanical recording media, and transmitted in the form of digital electrical or optical signals.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data pass in and out of computers via peripheral devices.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Physical computer memory elements consist of an address and a byte/word of data storage.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Digital data are often stored in relational databases, like tables or SQL databases, and can generally be represented as abstract key/value pairs.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data can be organized in many different types of data structures, including arrays, graphs, and objects.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data structures can store data of many different types, including numbers, strings and even other data structures.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Metadata helps translate data to information.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Metadata may be implied, specified or given.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data relating to physical events or processes will have a temporal component.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] This is the case when a device such as a temperature logger receives data from a temperature sensor.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] When the temperature is received it is assumed that the data has a temporal reference of *now*.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] So the device records the date, time and temperature together.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] When the data logger communicates temperatures, it must also report the date and time as metadata for each temperature reading.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Fundamentally, computers follow a sequence of instructions they are given in the form of data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] A set of instructions to perform a given task (or tasks) is called a *program*.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] A program is data in the form of coded instructions to control the operation of a computer or other machine.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In the nominal case, the program, as executed by the computer, will consist of machine code.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The elements of storage manipulated by the program, but not actually executed by the central processing unit (CPU), are also data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] At its most essential, a single datum is a value stored at a specific location.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Therefore, it is possible for computer programs to operate on other computer programs, by manipulating their programmatic data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] To store data bytes in a file, they have to be serialized in a file format.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Typically, programs are stored in special file types, different from those used for other data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Executable files contain programs; all other files are also data files.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] However, executable files may also contain data used by the program which is built into the program.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In particular, some executable files have a data segment, which nominally contains constants and initial values for variables, both of which can be considered data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The line between program and data can become blurry.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] An interpreter, for example, is a program.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The input data to an interpreter is itself a program, just not one expressed in native machine language.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In many cases, the interpreted program will be a human-readable text file, which is manipulated with a text editor program.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Metaprogramming similarly involves programs manipulating other programs as data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Programs like compilers, linkers, debuggers, program updaters, virus scanners and such use other programs as their data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] For example, a user might first instruct the operating system to load a word processor program from one file, and then use the running program to open and edit a document stored in another file.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In this example, the document would be considered data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] If the word processor also features a spell checker, then the dictionary (word list) for the spell checker would also be considered data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The algorithms used by the spell checker to suggest corrections would be either machine code data or text in some interpretable programming language.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In an alternate usage, binary files (which are not human-readable) are sometimes called *data* as distinguished from human-readable *text*.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The total amount of digital data in 2007 was estimated to be 281 billion gigabytes (281 exabytes).
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Keys in data provide the context for values.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Regardless of the structure of data, there is always a key component present.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Keys in data and data-structures are essential for giving meaning to data values.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Without a key that is directly or indirectly associated with a value, or collection of values in a structure, the values become meaningless and cease to be data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] That is to say, there has to be a key component linked to a value component in order for it to be considered data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Random access memory (RAM) holds data that the CPU has direct access to.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] A CPU may only manipulate data within its processor registers or memory.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] This is as opposed to data storage, where the CPU must direct the transfer of data between the storage device (disk, tape...) and memory.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] RAM is an array of linear contiguous locations that a processor may read or write by providing an address for the read or write operation.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The processor may operate on any location in memory at any time in any order.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In RAM the smallest element of data is the binary bit.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The capabilities and limitations of accessing RAM are processor specific.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In general main memory is arranged as an array of locations beginning at address 0 (hexadecimal 0).
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Each location can store usually 8 or 32 bits depending on the computer architecture.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data keys need not be a direct hardware address in memory.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Indirect, abstract and logical keys codes can be stored in association with values to form a data structure.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data structures have predetermined offsets (or links or paths) from the start of the structure, in which data values are stored.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Therefore, the data key consists of the key to the structure plus the offset (or links or paths) into the structure.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In such an organization of data, the data key is usually a value in one (or a composite of the values in several) of the columns.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The tabular view of repeating data structures is only one of many possibilities.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Repeating data structures can be organised hierarchically, such that nodes are linked to each other in a cascade of parent-child relationships.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Values and potentially more complex data-structures are linked to the nodes.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Thus the nodal hierarchy provides the key for addressing the data structures associated with the nodes.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] This representation can be thought of as an inverted tree.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Modern computer operating system file systems are a common example; and XML is another.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Data has some inherent features when it is sorted on a key.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] All the values for subsets of the key appear together.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] When passing sequentially through groups of the data with the same key, or a subset of the key changes, this is referred to in data processing circles as a break, or a control break.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] It particularly facilitates the aggregation of data values on subsets of a key.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Until the advent of bulk non-volatile memory like flash, persistent data storage was traditionally achieved by writing the data to external block devices like magnetic tape and disk drives.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] These devices typically seek to a location on the magnetic media and then read or write blocks of data of a predetermined size.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In this case, the seek location on the media, is the data key and the blocks are the data values.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Early used *raw disk* data file-systems or disc operating systems reserved contiguous blocks on the disc drive for data files.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In those systems, the files could be filled up, running out of data space before all the data had been written to them.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Thus much unused data space was reserved unproductively to ensure adequate free space for each file.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Later file-systems introduced partitions.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] They reserved blocks of disc data space for partitions and used the allocated blocks more economically, by dynamically assigning blocks of a partition to a file as needed.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] To achieve this, the file system had to keep track of which blocks were used or unused by data files in a catalog or file allocation table.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Though this made better use of the disc data space, it resulted in fragmentation of files across the disc, and a concomitant performance overhead due additional seek time to read the data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Modern file systems reorganize fragmented files dynamically to optimize file access times.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Further developments in file systems resulted in virtualization of disc drives i.e. where a logical drive can be defined as partitions from a number of physical drives.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Retrieving a small subset of data from a much larger set may imply inefficiently searching through the data sequentially.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] **Indexes** are a way to copy out keys and location addresses from data structures in files, tables and data sets, then organize them using inverted tree structures to reduce the time taken to retrieve a subset of the original data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In order to do this, the key of the subset of data to be retrieved must be known before retrieval begins.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The most popular indexes are the B-tree and the dynamic hash key indexing methods.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Indexing is overhead for filing and retrieving data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] There are other ways of organizing indexes, e.g. sorting the keys and using a binary search algorithm.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] 2. at run time, the creation of references to in-memory data-structures of objects that have been instantiated from a class library.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] It is only after instantiation that an object of a specified class exists.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] After an object's reference is cleared, the object also ceases to exist.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The memory locations where the object's data was stored are garbage and are reclassified as unused memory available for reuse.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] The advent of databases introduced a further layer of abstraction for persistent data storage.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Databases use metadata, and a structured query language protocol between client and server systems, communicating over a computer network, using a two phase commit logging system to ensure transactional completeness, when saving data.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Modern scalable and high-performance data persistence technologies, such as Apache Hadoop, rely on massively parallel distributed data processing across many commodity computers on a high bandwidth network.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] In such systems, the data is distributed across multiple computers and therefore any particular computer in the system must be represented in the key of the data, either directly, or indirectly.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] This enables the differentiation between two identical sets of data, each being processed on a different computer at the same time.
[src:confidential-computing/data-in-use] Even though digital signals are generally associated with the binary electronic digital systems used in modern electronics and computing, digital systems are actually ancient, and need not be binary or electronic.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] As an example of a practical application of homomorphic encryption: encrypted photographs can be scanned for points of interest, without revealing the contents of a photo.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] However, observation of side-channels can see a photograph being sent to a point-of-interest lookup service, revealing the fact that photographs were taken.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Thus, homomorphic encryption eliminates the need for processing data in the clear, thereby preventing attacks that would enable an attacker to access that data while it is being processed, using privilege escalation.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] For sensitive data, such as healthcare information, homomorphic encryption can be used to enable new services by removing privacy barriers inhibiting data sharing or increasing security to existing services.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] For example, predictive analytics in healthcare can be hard to apply via a third-party service provider due to medical data privacy concerns.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] But if the predictive-analytics service provider could operate on encrypted data instead, without having the decryption keys, these privacy concerns are diminished.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Moreover, even if the service provider's system is compromised, the data would remain secure.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption is a form of encryption with an additional evaluation capability for computing over encrypted data without access to the secret key.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The result of such a computation remains encrypted.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption can be viewed as an extension of public-key cryptography, because ciphertexts can be manipulated algebraically to produce an encrypted result corresponding to operations on the underlying plaintexts.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] *Homomorphic* refers to homomorphism in algebra: the encryption and decryption functions can be thought of as homomorphisms between plaintext and ciphertext spaces.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption includes multiple types of encryption schemes that can perform different classes of computations over encrypted data.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The computations are represented as either Boolean or arithmetic circuits.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] For the majority of homomorphic encryption schemes, the multiplicative depth of circuits is the main practical limitation in performing computations over encrypted data.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption schemes are inherently malleable.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] In terms of malleability, homomorphic encryption schemes have weaker security properties than non-homomorphic schemes.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] A cryptosystem that supports *arbitrary computation* on ciphertexts is known as fully homomorphic encryption (FHE).
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Such a scheme enables the construction of programs for any desirable functionality, which can be run on encrypted inputs to produce an encryption of the result.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Since such a program need never decrypt its inputs, it can be run by an untrusted party without revealing its inputs and internal state.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Fully homomorphic cryptosystems have great practical implications in the outsourcing of private computations, for instance, in the context of cloud computing.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption schemes have been developed using different approaches.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Specifically, fully homomorphic encryption schemes are often grouped into generations corresponding to the underlying approach.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The problem of constructing a fully homomorphic encryption scheme was first proposed in 1978, within a year of publishing of the RSA scheme.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] For more than 30 years, it was unclear whether a solution existed.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Craig Gentry, using lattice-based cryptography, described the first plausible construction for a fully homomorphic encryption scheme in 2009.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry's scheme supports both addition and multiplication operations on ciphertexts, from which it is possible to construct circuits for performing arbitrary computation.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry then shows how to slightly modify this scheme to make it *bootstrappable*, i.e., capable of evaluating its own decryption circuit and then at least one more operation.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Finally, he shows that any bootstrappable somewhat homomorphic encryption scheme can be converted into a fully homomorphic encryption through a recursive self-embedding.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] For Gentry's "noisy" scheme, the bootstrapping procedure effectively "refreshes" the ciphertext by applying to it the decryption procedure homomorphically, thereby obtaining a new ciphertext that encrypts the same value as before but has lower noise.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] By "refreshing" the ciphertext periodically whenever the noise grows too large, it is possible to compute an arbitrary number of additions and multiplications without increasing the noise too much.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry based the security of his scheme on the assumed hardness of two problems: certain worst-case problems over ideal lattices, and the sparse (or low-weight) subset sum problem.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry's Ph.D. thesis provides additional details.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The Gentry-Halevi implementation of Gentry's original cryptosystem reported a timing of about 30 minutes per basic bit operation.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Extensive design and implementation work in subsequent years have improved upon these early implementations by many orders of magnitude runtime performance.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] In 2010, Marten van Dijk, Craig Gentry, Shai Halevi and Vinod Vaikuntanathan presented a second fully homomorphic encryption scheme, which uses many of the tools of Gentry's construction, but which does not require ideal lattices.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Instead, they show that the somewhat homomorphic component of Gentry's ideal lattice-based scheme can be replaced with a very simple somewhat homomorphic scheme that uses integers.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The scheme is therefore conceptually simpler than Gentry's ideal lattice scheme, but has similar properties with regards to homomorphic operations and efficiency.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The somewhat homomorphic component in the work of Van Dijk et al. is similar to an encryption scheme proposed by Levieil and Naccache in 2008, and also to one that was proposed by Bram Cohen in 1998.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Cohen's method is not even additively homomorphic, however.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The Levieil–Naccache scheme supports only additions, but it can be modified to also support a small number of multiplications.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Many refinements and optimizations of the scheme of Van Dijk et al. were proposed in a sequence of works by Jean-Sébastien Coron, Tancrède Lepoint, Avradip Mandal, David Naccache, and Mehdi Tibouchi.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Some of these works included also implementations of the resulting schemes.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The homomorphic cryptosystems of this generation are derived from techniques that were developed starting in 2011–2012 by Zvika Brakerski, Craig Gentry, Vinod Vaikuntanathan, and others.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] These innovations led to the development of much more efficient somewhat and fully homomorphic cryptosystems.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The security of most of these schemes is based on the hardness of the (Ring) Learning With Errors (RLWE) problem, except for the LTV and BLLN schemes that rely on an *overstretched* variant of the NTRU computational problem.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] This NTRU variant was subsequently shown vulnerable to subfield lattice attacks, which is why these two schemes are no longer used in practice.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] All the second-generation cryptosystems still follow the basic blueprint of Gentry's original construction, namely they first construct a somewhat homomorphic cryptosystem and then convert it to a fully homomorphic cryptosystem using bootstrapping.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] A distinguishing characteristic of the second-generation cryptosystems is that they all feature a much slower growth of the noise during the homomorphic computations.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Additional optimizations by Craig Gentry, Shai Halevi, and Nigel Smart resulted in cryptosystems with nearly optimal asymptotic complexity: Performing T operations on data encrypted with security parameter k has complexity of only $T\cdot \mathrm {polylog} (k)$ .
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] These optimizations build on the Smart-Vercauteren techniques that enable packing of many plaintext values in a single ciphertext and operating on all these plaintext values in a SIMD fashion.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Many of the advances in these second-generation cryptosystems were also ported to the cryptosystem over the integers.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Another distinguishing feature of second-generation schemes is that they are efficient enough for many applications even without invoking bootstrapping, instead operating in the leveled FHE mode.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] In 2013, Craig Gentry, Amit Sahai, and Brent Waters (GSW) proposed a new technique for building FHE schemes that avoids an expensive "relinearization" step in homomorphic multiplication.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Zvika Brakerski and Vinod Vaikuntanathan observed that for certain types of circuits, the GSW cryptosystem features an even slower growth rate of noise, and hence better efficiency and stronger security.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Jacob Alperin-Sheriff and Chris Peikert then described a very efficient bootstrapping technique based on this observation.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] These techniques were further improved to develop efficient ring variants of the GSW cryptosystem: FHEW (2014) and TFHE (2016).
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The FHEW scheme was the first to show that by refreshing the ciphertexts after every single operation, it is possible to reduce the bootstrapping time to a fraction of a second.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] FHEW introduced a new method to compute Boolean gates on encrypted data that greatly simplifies bootstrapping and implemented a variant of the bootstrapping procedure.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The efficiency of FHEW was further improved by the TFHE scheme, which implements a ring variant of the bootstrapping procedure using a method similar to the one in FHEW.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] In 2016, Jung Hee Cheon, Andrey Kim, Miran Kim, and Yongsoo Song (CKKS) proposed an approximate homomorphic encryption scheme that supports a special kind of fixed-point arithmetic that is commonly referred to as block floating point arithmetic.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The CKKS scheme includes an efficient rescaling operation that scales down an encrypted message after a multiplication.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] For comparison, such rescaling requires bootstrapping in the BGV and BFV schemes.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The rescaling operation makes CKKS scheme the most efficient method for evaluating polynomial approximations, and is the preferred approach for implementing privacy-preserving machine learning applications.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The scheme introduces several approximation errors, both nondeterministic and deterministic, that require special handling in practice.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] A 2020 article by Baiyu Li and Daniele Micciancio discusses passive attacks against CKKS, suggesting that the standard IND-CPA definition may not be sufficient in scenarios where decryption results are shared.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The authors apply the attack to four modern homomorphic encryption libraries (HEAAN, SEAL, HElib and PALISADE) and report that it is possible to recover the secret key from decryption results in several parameter configurations.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The authors also propose mitigation strategies for these attacks, and include a Responsible Disclosure in the paper suggesting that the homomorphic encryption libraries already implemented mitigations for the attacks before the article became publicly available.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Further information on the mitigation strategies implemented in the homomorphic encryption libraries has also been published.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] In the following examples, the notation ${\mathcal {E}}(x)$ is used to denote the encryption of the message x .
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] where $\oplus$ denotes addition modulo 2, (i.e., exclusive-or).
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] There are several open-source implementations of partially, somewhat and fully homomorphic encryption schemes.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Second-generation and fourth-generation FHE scheme implementations typically operate in the leveled FHE mode (though bootstrapping is still available in some libraries) and support efficient SIMD-like packing of data; they are typically used to compute on encrypted integers or real/complex numbers.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Third-generation FHE scheme implementations often bootstrap after each operation but have limited support for packing; they were initially used to compute Boolean circuits over encrypted bits, but have been extended to support integer arithmetics and univariate function evaluation.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] The choice of using a second-generation vs. third-generation vs fourth-generation scheme depends on the input data types and the desired computation.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] General-purpose lattice cryptography library.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] TFHE-extended compiler with a Python Frontend.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] Verifiable encrypted computations based on Rinocchio ZKP and BGV homomorphic Encryption.
[src:confidential-computing/homomorphic-encryption] In 2017, researchers from IBM, Microsoft, Intel, the NIST, and others formed the open Homomorphic Encryption Standardization Consortium, which maintains a community security Homomorphic Encryption Standard.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing proponents such as International Data Corporation, the Enterprise Strategy Group and Endpoint Technologies Associates state that the technology will make computers safer, less prone to viruses and malware, and thus more reliable from an end-user perspective.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] They also state that Trusted Computing will allow computers and servers to offer improved computer security over that which is currently available.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Opponents often state that this technology will be used primarily to enforce digital rights management policies (imposed restrictions to the owner) and not to increase computer security.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Chip manufacturers Intel and AMD, hardware manufacturers such as HP and Dell, and operating system providers such as Microsoft include Trusted Computing in their products if enabled.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Army requires that every new PC it purchases comes with a Trusted Platform Module (TPM).
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] As of July 3, 2007, so does virtually the entire United States Department of Defense.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The endorsement key is a 2048-bit RSA public and private key pair that is created randomly on the chip at manufacture time and cannot be changed.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The private key never leaves the chip, while the public key is used for attestation and for encryption of sensitive data sent to the chip, as occurs during the TPM_TakeOwnership command.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The TPM should be designed to make the extraction of this key by hardware analysis hard, but tamper resistance is not a strong requirement.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Memory curtaining extends common memory protection techniques to provide full isolation of sensitive areas of memory—for example, locations containing cryptographic keys.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Even the operating system does not have full access to curtained memory.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The exact implementation details are vendor specific.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Sealed storage protects private information by binding it to platform configuration information including the software and hardware being used.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] This means the data can be released only to a particular combination of software and hardware.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Sealed storage can be used for DRM enforcing.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] For example, users who keep a song on their computer that has not been licensed to be listened will not be able to play it.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Currently, a user can locate the song, listen to it, and send it to someone else, play it in the software of their choice, or back it up (and in some cases, use circumvention software to decrypt it).
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Alternatively, the user may use software to modify the operating system's DRM routines to have it leak the song data once, say, a temporary license was acquired.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Using sealed storage, the song is securely encrypted using a key bound to the trusted platform module so that only the unmodified and untampered music player on his or her computer can play it.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] In this DRM architecture, this might also prevent people from listening to the song after buying a new computer, or upgrading parts of their current one, except after explicit permission of the vendor of the song.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Remote attestation allows changes to the user's computer to be detected by authorized parties.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] For example, software companies can identify unauthorized changes to software, including users modifying their software to circumvent commercial digital rights restrictions.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] It works by having the hardware generate a certificate stating what software is currently running.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The computer can then present this certificate to a remote party to show that unaltered software is currently executing.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Numerous remote attestation schemes have been proposed for various computer architectures, including Intel, RISC-V, and ARM.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Remote attestation is usually combined with public-key encryption so that the information sent can only be read by the programs that requested the attestation, and not by an eavesdropper.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] To take the song example again, the user's music player software could send the song to other machines, but only if they could attest that they were running an authorized copy of the music player software.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] To preserve the privacy of attestation responders, Direct Anonymous Attestation has been proposed as a solution, which uses a group signature scheme to prevent revealing the identity of individual signers.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Proof of space (PoS) have been proposed to be used for malware detection, by determining whether the L1 cache of a processor is empty (e.g., has enough space to evaluate the PoSpace routine without cache misses) or contains a routine that resisted being evicted.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The Microsoft products Windows Vista, Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows RT make use of a Trusted Platform Module to facilitate BitLocker Drive Encryption.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Other known applications with runtime encryption and the use of secure enclaves include the Signal messenger and the e-prescription service ("E-Rezept") by the German government.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing would allow companies to create a digital rights management (DRM) system which would be very hard to circumvent, though not impossible.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Sealed storage could be used to prevent the user from opening the file with an unauthorized player or computer.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Remote attestation could be used to authorize play only by music players that enforce the record company's rules.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The music would be played from curtained memory, which would prevent the user from making an unrestricted copy of the file while it is playing, and secure I/O would prevent capturing what is being sent to the sound system.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Circumventing such a system would require either manipulation of the computer's hardware, capturing the analogue (and thus degraded) signal using a recording device or a microphone, or breaking the security of the system.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] New business models for use of software (services) over Internet may be boosted by the technology.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] By strengthening the DRM system, one could base a business model on renting programs for a specific time periods or "pay as you go" models.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] For instance, one could download a music file which could only be played a certain number of times before it becomes unusable, or the music file could be used only within a certain time period.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing could be used to combat cheating in online games.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Some players modify their game copy in order to gain unfair advantages in the game; remote attestation, secure I/O and memory curtaining could be used to determine that all players connected to a server were running an unmodified copy of the software.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing could be used to guarantee participants in a grid computing system are returning the results of the computations they claim to be instead of forging them.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] This would allow large scale simulations to be run (say a climate simulation) without expensive redundant computations to guarantee malicious hosts are not undermining the results to achieve the conclusion they want.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The Electronic Frontier Foundation and the Free Software Foundation criticize that trust in the underlying companies is not deserved and that the technology puts too much power and control into the hands of those who design systems and software.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] They also state that it may cause consumers to lose anonymity in their online interactions, as well as mandating technologies Trusted Computing opponents say are unnecessary.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] They suggest Trusted Computing as a possible enabler for future versions of mandatory access control, copy protection, and DRM.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Some security experts, such as Alan Cox and Bruce Schneier, have spoken out against Trusted Computing, believing it will provide computer manufacturers and software authors with increased control to impose restrictions on what users are able to do with their computers.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] There are concerns that Trusted Computing would have an anti-competitive effect on the IT market.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] There is concern amongst critics that it will not always be possible to examine the hardware components on which Trusted Computing relies, the Trusted Platform Module, which is the ultimate hardware system where the core 'root' of trust in the platform has to reside.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] If not implemented correctly, it presents a security risk to overall platform integrity and protected data.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The specifications, as published by the Trusted Computing Group, are open and are available for anyone to review.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] However, the final implementations by commercial vendors will not necessarily be subjected to the same review process.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] In addition, the world of cryptography can often move quickly, and that hardware implementations of algorithms might create an inadvertent obsolescence.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Trusting networked computers to controlling authorities rather than to individuals may create digital imprimaturs.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] One of the early motivations behind trusted computing was a desire by media and software corporations for stricter DRM technology to prevent users from freely sharing and using potentially copyrighted or private files without explicit permission.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] An example could be downloading a music file from a band: the band's record company could come up with rules for how the band's music can be used.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] For example, they might want the user to play the file only three times a day without paying additional money.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Also, they could use remote attestation to only send their music to a music player that enforces their rules: sealed storage would prevent the user from opening the file with another player that did not enforce the restrictions.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Memory curtaining would prevent the user from making an unrestricted copy of the file while it is playing, and secure output would prevent capturing what is sent to the sound system.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] A user who wanted to switch to a competing program might find that it would be impossible for that new program to read old data, as the information would be "locked in" to the old program.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] It could also make it impossible for the user to read or modify their data except as specifically permitted by the software.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The law in many countries allows users certain rights over data whose copyright they do not own (including text, images, and other media), often under headings such as fair use or public interest.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Depending on jurisdiction, these may cover issues such as whistleblowing, production of evidence in court, quoting or other small-scale usage, backups of owned media, and making a copy of owned material for personal use on other owned devices or systems.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The steps implicit in trusted computing have the practical effect of preventing users exercising these legal rights.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] A service that requires external validation or permission - such as a music file or game that requires connection with the vendor to confirm permission to play or use - is vulnerable to that service being withdrawn or no longer updated.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] A number of incidents have already occurred where users, having purchased music or video media, have found their ability to watch or listen to it suddenly stop due to vendor policy or cessation of service, or server inaccessibility, at times with no compensation.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Alternatively in some cases the vendor refuses to provide services in future which leaves purchased material only usable on the present -and increasingly obsolete- hardware (so long as it lasts) but not on any hardware that may be purchased in future.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Some opponents of Trusted Computing advocate "owner override": allowing an owner who is confirmed to be physically present to allow the computer to bypass restrictions and use the secure I/O path.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Such an override would allow remote attestation to a user's specification, e.g., to create certificates that say Internet Explorer is running, even if a different browser is used.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Instead of preventing software change, remote attestation would indicate when the software has been changed without owner's permission.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing Group members have refused to implement owner override.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Proponents of trusted computing believe that owner override defeats the trust in other computers since remote attestation can be forged by the owner.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Owner override offers the security and enforcement benefits to a machine owner, but does not allow them to trust other computers, because their owners could waive rules or restrictions on their own computers.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Under this scenario, once data is sent to someone else's computer, whether it be a diary, a DRM music file, or a joint project, that other person controls what security, if any, their computer will enforce on their copy of those data.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] This has the potential to undermine the applications of trusted computing to enforce DRM, control cheating in online games and attest to remote computations for grid computing.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Because a Trusted Computing equipped computer is able to uniquely attest to its own identity, it will be possible for vendors and others who possess the ability to use the attestation feature to zero in on the identity of the user of TC-enabled software with a high degree of certainty.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Such a capability is contingent on the reasonable chance that the user at some time provides user-identifying information, whether voluntarily, indirectly, or simply through inference of many seemingly benign pieces of data.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] (e.g. search records, as shown through simple study of the AOL search records leak).
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] One common way that information can be obtained and linked is when a user registers a computer just after purchase.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Another common way is when a user provides identifying information to the website of an affiliate of the vendor.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] While proponents of TC point out that online purchases and credit transactions could potentially be more secure as a result of the remote attestation capability, this may cause the computer user to lose expectations of anonymity when using the Internet.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Critics point out that this could have a chilling effect on political free speech, the ability of journalists to use anonymous sources, whistle blowing, political blogging and other areas where the public needs protection from retaliation through anonymity.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The TPM specification offers features and suggested implementations that are meant to address the anonymity requirement.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] By using a third-party Privacy Certification Authority (PCA), the information that identifies the computer could be held by a trusted third party.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Additionally, the use of direct anonymous attestation (DAA), introduced in TPM v1.2, allows a client to perform attestation while not revealing any personally identifiable or machine information.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The kind of data that must be supplied to the TTP in order to get the trusted status is at present not entirely clear, but the TCG itself admits that "attestation is an important TPM function with significant privacy implications".
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] It is, however, clear that both static and dynamic information about the user computer may be supplied (Ekpubkey) to the TTP (v1.1b), it is not clear what data will be supplied to the “verifier” under v1.2.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The static information will uniquely identify the endorser of the platform, model, details of the TPM, and that the platform (PC) complies with the TCG specifications .
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The dynamic information is described as software running on the computer.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] If a program like Windows is registered in the user's name this in turn will uniquely identify the user.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Another dimension of privacy infringing capabilities might also be introduced with this new technology; how often you use your programs might be possible information provided to the TTP.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] In an exceptional, however practical situation, where a user purchases a pornographic movie on the Internet, the purchaser nowadays, must accept the fact that he has to provide credit card details to the provider, thereby possibly risking being identified.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] With the new technology a purchaser might also risk someone finding out that he (or she) has watched this pornographic movie 1000 times.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] This adds a new dimension to the possible privacy infringement.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The extent of data that will be supplied to the TTP/Verifiers is at present not exactly known, only when the technology is implemented and used will we be able to assess the exact nature and volume of the data that is transmitted.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing requests that all software and hardware vendors will follow the technical specifications released by the Trusted Computing Group in order to allow interoperability between different trusted software stacks.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] However, since at least mid-2006, there have been interoperability problems between the TrouSerS trusted software stack (released as open source software by IBM) and Hewlett-Packard's stack.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Another problem is that the technical specifications are still changing, so it is unclear which is the standard implementation of the trusted stack.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] People have voiced concerns that trusted computing could be used to keep or discourage users from running software created by companies outside of a small industry group.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The concerns about trusted computing being used to shut out competition exist within a broader framework of consumers being concerned about using bundling of products to obscure prices of products and to engage in anti-competitive practices.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing is seen as harmful or problematic to independent and open source software developers.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] In the widely used public-key cryptography, creation of keys can be done on the local computer and the creator has complete control over who has access to it, and consequentially their own security policies.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] In some proposed encryption-decryption chips, a private/public key is permanently embedded into the hardware when it is manufactured, and hardware manufacturers would have the opportunity to record the key without leaving evidence of doing so.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] With this key it would be possible to have access to data encrypted with it, and to authenticate as it.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] It is trivial for a manufacturer to give a copy of this key to the government or the software manufacturers, as the platform must go through steps so that it works with authenticated software.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] A security breach breaking that chain of trust happened to a SIM card manufacturer Gemalto, which in 2010 was infiltrated by US and British spies, resulting in compromised security of cellphone calls.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] It is also critical that one be able to trust that the hardware manufacturers and software developers properly implement trusted computing standards.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Incorrect implementation could be hidden from users, and thus could undermine the integrity of the whole system without users being aware of the flaw.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Since 2004, most major manufacturers have shipped systems that have included Trusted Platform Modules, with associated BIOS support.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] In accordance with the TCG specifications, the user must enable the Trusted Platform Module before it can be used.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Processor manufacturers have included secure enclaves in their design such as ARM TrustZone, Intel Management Engine with SGX and AMD PSP with Secure Encrypted Virtualization.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The Linux kernel has included trusted computing support since version 2.6.13, and there are several projects to implement trusted computing for Linux.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] In January 2005, members of Gentoo Linux's "crypto herd" announced their intention of providing support for TC—in particular support for the Trusted Platform Module.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] There is also a TCG-compliant software stack for Linux named TrouSerS, released under an open source license.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] There are several open-source projects that facilitate the use of confidential computing technology, including EGo, EdgelessDB and MarbleRun from Edgeless Systems, as well as Enarx, which originates from security research at Red Hat.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Some limited form of trusted computing can be implemented on current versions of Microsoft Windows with third-party software.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Major cloud providers such as Microsoft Azure, AWS and Google Cloud Platform have virtual machines with trusted computing features available.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] The Intel Classmate PC (a competitor to the One Laptop Per Child) includes a Trusted Platform Module.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] PrivateCore vCage software can be used to attest x86 servers with TPM chips.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Google enforces Play Integrity API to Android devices with their bootloader unlocked.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Mobile T6 secure operating system simulates the TPM functionality in mobile devices using the ARM TrustZone technology.
[src:confidential-computing/remote-attestation] Samsung smartphones come equipped with Samsung Knox that depend on features like Secure Boot, TIMA, MDM, TrustZone and SE Linux.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] SGX involves encryption by the CPU of a portion of memory (the *enclave*).
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Data and code originating in the enclave are decrypted on the fly *within* the CPU, protecting them from being examined or read by other code, including code running at higher privilege levels such as the operating system and any underlying hypervisors.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] While this can mitigate many kinds of attacks, it does not protect against side-channel attacks.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] A pivot by Intel in 2021 resulted in the deprecation of SGX from the 11th and 12th generation Intel Core processors, but development continues on Intel Xeon for cloud and enterprise use.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] SGX was first introduced in 2015 with the sixth generation Intel Core microprocessors based on the Skylake microarchitecture.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Support for SGX in the CPU is indicated in CPUID "Structured Extended feature Leaf", EBX bit 02, but its availability to applications requires BIOS/UEFI support and opt-in enabling which is not reflected in CPUID bits.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] This complicates the feature detection logic for applications.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Emulation of SGX was added to an experimental version of the QEMU system emulator in 2014.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] In 2015, researchers at the Georgia Institute of Technology released an open-source simulator named "OpenSGX".
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] One example of SGX used in security was a demo application from wolfSSL using it for cryptography algorithms.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Intel Goldmont Plus (Gemini Lake) microarchitecture also contains support for Intel SGX.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Both in the 11th and 12th generations of Intel Core processors, SGX is listed as "Deprecated" and thereby not supported on "client platform" processors.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] This removed support of playing Ultra HD Blu-ray discs on officially licensed software, such as PowerDVD.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] On 27 March 2017 researchers at Austria's Graz University of Technology developed a proof-of-concept that can grab RSA keys from SGX enclaves running on the same system within five minutes by using certain CPU instructions in lieu of a fine-grained timer to exploit cache DRAM side-channels.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] One countermeasure for this type of attack was presented and published by Daniel Gruss et al. at the USENIX Security Symposium in 2017.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Among other published countermeasures, one countermeasure to this type of attack was published on September 28, 2017, a compiler-based tool, DR.SGX, that claims to have superior performance with the elimination of the implementation complexity of other proposed solutions.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] The LSDS group at Imperial College London showed a proof of concept that the Spectre speculative execution security vulnerability can be adapted to attack the secure enclave.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] The Foreshadow attack, disclosed in August 2018, combines speculative execution and buffer overflow to bypass the SGX.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] A security advisory and mitigation for this attack, also called an L1 Terminal Fault, was originally issued on August 14, 2018 and updated May 11, 2021.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] On 8 February 2019, researchers at Austria's Graz University of Technology published findings which showed that in some cases it is possible to run malicious code from within the enclave itself.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] The exploit involves scanning through process memory in order to reconstruct a payload, which can then run code on the system.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] The paper claims that due to the confidential and protected nature of the enclave, it is impossible for antivirus software to detect and remove malware residing within it.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Intel issued a statement, stating that this attack was outside the threat model of SGX, that they cannot guarantee that code run by the user comes from trusted sources, and urged consumers to only run trusted code.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] There is a proliferation of side-channel attacks plaguing modern computer architectures.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Many of these attacks measure slight, nondeterministic variations in the execution of code, so the attacker needs many measurements (possibly tens of thousands) to learn secrets.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] However, the MicroScope attack allows a malicious OS to replay code an arbitrary number of times regardless of the program's actual structure, enabling dozens of side-channel attacks.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] In July 2022, Intel submitted a Linux patch called AEX-Notify to allow the SGX enclave programmer to write a handler for these types of events.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Security researchers were able to inject timing specific faults into execution within the enclave, resulting in leakage of information.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] The attack can be executed remotely, but requires access to the privileged control of the processor's voltage and frequency.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] A security advisory and mitigation for this attack was originally issued on August 14, 2018 and updated on March 20, 2020.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Load Value Injection injects data into a program aiming to replace the value loaded from memory which is then used for a short time before the mistake is spotted and rolled back, during which LVI controls data and control flow.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] A security advisory and mitigation for this attack was originally issued on March 10, 2020 and updated on May 11, 2021.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] SGAxe, an SGX vulnerability published in 2020, extends a speculative execution attack on cache, leaking content of the enclave.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] This allows an attacker to access private CPU keys used for remote attestation.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] In other words, a threat actor can bypass Intel's countermeasures to breach SGX enclaves' confidentiality.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] The SGAxe attack is carried out by extracting attestation keys from SGX's private quoting enclave that are signed by Intel.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] The attacker can then masquerade as legitimate Intel machines by signing arbitrary SGX attestation quotes.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] A security advisory and mitigation for this attack, also called a Processor Data Leakage or Cache Eviction, was originally issued January 27, 2020 and updated May 11, 2021.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] In 2022, security researchers discovered a vulnerability in the Advanced Programmable Interrupt Controller (APIC) that allows for an attacker with root/admin privileges to gain access to encryption keys via the APIC by inspecting data transfers from L1 and L2 cache.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] This vulnerability is the first architectural attack discovered on x86 CPUs.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] This differs from Spectre and Meltdown which use a noisy side channel.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] This exploit currently affects Intel Core 10th, 11th and 12th generations, and Xeon Ice Lake microprocessors.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] There has been a long debate on whether SGX enables creation of superior malware.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Oxford University researchers published an article in October 2022 considering attackers' potential advantages and disadvantages by abusing SGX for malware development.
[src:confidential-computing/software-guard-extensions] Researchers conclude that while there might be temporary zero-day vulnerabilities to abuse in SGX ecosystem, the core principles and design features of Trusted Execution Environments (TEEs) make malware weaker than a malware-in-the-wild, TEEs make no major contributions to malware otherwise.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] A **trusted execution environment** (**TEE**) is a secure area of a main processor.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] It helps the code and data loaded inside it be protected with respect to confidentiality and integrity.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Data confidentiality prevents unauthorized entities from outside the TEE from reading data, while code integrity prevents code in the TEE from being replaced or modified by unauthorized entities, which may also be the computer owner itself as in certain DRM schemes described in Intel SGX.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] This is done by implementing unique, immutable, and confidential architectural security, which offers hardware-based memory encryption that isolates specific application code and data in memory.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] This allows user-level code to allocate private regions of memory, called enclaves, which are designed to be protected from processes running at higher privilege levels.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] A TEE as an isolated execution environment provides security features such as isolated execution, integrity of applications executing with the TEE, and confidentiality of their assets.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] In general terms, the TEE offers an execution space that provides a higher level of security for trusted applications running on the device than a rich operating system (OS) and more functionality than a 'secure element' (SE).
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The first security level, Profile 1, was targeted against only software attacks, while Profile 2, was targeted against both software and hardware attacks.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Commercial TEE solutions based on ARM TrustZone technology, conforming to the TR1 standard, were later launched, such as Trusted Foundations developed by Trusted Logic.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Work on the OMTP standards ended in mid-2010 when the group transitioned into the Wholesale Applications Community (WAC).
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The OMTP standards, including those defining a TEE, are hosted by GSMA.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE typically consists of a hardware isolation mechanism plus a secure operating system running on top of that isolation mechanism, although the term has been used more generally to mean a protected solution.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Whilst a GlobalPlatform TEE requires hardware isolation, others, such as EMVCo, use the term TEE to refer to both hardware and software-based solutions.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] FIDO uses the concept of TEE in the restricted operating environment for TEEs based on hardware isolation.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Only trusted applications running in a TEE have access to the full power of a device's main processor, peripherals, and memory, while hardware isolation protects these from user-installed apps running in a main operating system.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Software and cryptography inside the TEE protects the trusted applications contained within from each other.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Service providers, mobile network operators (MNO), operating system developers, application developers, device manufacturers, platform providers, and silicon vendors are the main stakeholders contributing to the standardization efforts around the TEE.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] To prevent the simulation of hardware with user-controlled software, a so-called "hardware root of trust" is used.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] This is a set of private keys that are embedded directly into the chip during manufacturing; one-time programmable memory such as eFuses is usually used on mobile devices.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The hardware is designed in a way that prevents all software not signed by the trusted party's key from accessing the privileged features.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The public key of the vendor is provided at runtime and hashed; this hash is then compared to the one embedded in the chip.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] If the hash matches, the public key is used to verify a digital signature of trusted vendor-controlled firmware (such as a chain of bootloaders on Android devices or 'architectural enclaves' in SGX).
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The trusted firmware is then used to implement remote attestation.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] When an application is attested, its untrusted components loads its trusted component into memory; the trusted application is protected from modification by untrusted components with hardware.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] A nonce is requested by the untrusted party from the verifier's server and is used as part of a cryptographic authentication protocol, proving integrity of the trusted application.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The proof is passed to the verifier, which verifies it.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] A valid proof cannot be computed in simulated hardware (i.e.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] QEMU) because in order to construct it, access to the keys baked into hardware is required; only trusted firmware has access to these keys and/or the keys derived from them or obtained using them.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Because only the platform owner is meant to have access to the data recorded in the foundry, the verifying party must interact with the service set up by the vendor.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] If the scheme is implemented improperly, the chip vendor can track which applications are used on which chip and selectively deny service by returning a message indicating that authentication has not passed.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] To simulate hardware in a way that enables it to pass remote authentication, an attacker would have to extract keys from the hardware, which is costly because of the equipment and technical skill required to execute it.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] For example, using focused ion beams, scanning electron microscopes, microprobing, and chip decapsulation is difficult, or even impossible, if the hardware is designed in such a way that reverse-engineering destroys the keys.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] In most cases, the keys are unique for each piece of hardware, so that a key extracted from one chip cannot be used by others (for example physically unclonable functions).
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Note: Much TEE literature covers this topic under the definition "premium content protection," which is the preferred nomenclature of many copyright holders.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Premium content protection is a specific use case of digital rights management (DRM) and is controversial among some communities, such as the Free Software Foundation.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] It is widely used by copyright holders to restrict the ways in which end users can consume content such as 4K high-definition films.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is a suitable environment for protecting digitally encoded information (for example, HD films or audio) on connected devices such as smartphones, tablets, and HD televisions.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] This suitability comes from the ability of the TEE to deprive the owner of the device of access stored secrets, and the fact that there is often a protected hardware path between the TEE and the display and/or subsystems on devices.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is used to protect the content once it is on the device.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] While the content is protected during transmission or streaming by the use of encryption, the TEE protects the content once it has been decrypted on the device by ensuring that decrypted content is not exposed to the environment not approved by the app developer or platform vendor.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Mobile commerce applications such as: mobile wallets, peer-to-peer payments, contactless payments or using a mobile device as a point of sale (POS) terminal often have well-defined security requirements.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] In some scenarios, interaction with the end user is required, and this may require the user to expose sensitive information such as a PIN, password, or biometric identifier to the mobile OS as a means of authenticating the user.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE optionally offers a trusted user interface which can be used to construct user authentication on a mobile device.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] With the rise of cryptocurrency, TEEs are increasingly used to implement crypto-wallets, as they offer the ability to store tokens more securely than regular operating systems, and can provide the necessary computation and authentication applications.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is well-suited for supporting biometric identification methods (facial recognition, fingerprint sensor, and voice authorization), which may be easier to use and harder to steal than PINs and passwords.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] A TEE is a good area within a mobile device to house the matching engine and the associated processing required to authenticate the user.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The environment is designed to protect the data and establish a buffer against the non-secure apps located in mobile OSes.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] This additional security may help to satisfy the security needs of service providers in addition to keeping the costs low for handset developers.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE can be used by governments, enterprises, and cloud service providers to enable the secure handling of confidential information on mobile devices and on server infrastructure.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE offers a level of protection against software attacks generated in the mobile OS and assists in the control of access rights.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] It achieves this by housing sensitive, ‘trusted’ applications that need to be isolated and protected from the mobile OS and any malicious malware that may be present.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Through utilizing the functionality and security levels offered by the TEE, governments, and enterprises can be assured that employees using their own devices are doing so in a secure and trusted manner.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] Likewise, server-based TEEs help defend against internal and external attacks against backend infrastructure.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] With the rise of software assets and reuses, modular programming is the most productive process to design software architecture, by decoupling the functionalities into small independent modules.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] As each module contains everything necessary to execute its desired functionality, the TEE allows the organization of the complete system featuring a high level of reliability and security, while preventing each module from vulnerabilities of the others.
[src:confidential-computing/trusted-execution-environment] In order for the modules to communicate and share data, TEE provides means to securely have payloads sent/received between the modules, using mechanisms such as object serialization, in conjunction with proxies.
